# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: futhark-lang
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:futhark-lang/data-parallelism] A data parallel job on an array of *n* elements can be divided equally among all the processors.
[src:futhark-lang/data-parallelism] Let us assume we want to sum all the elements of the given array and the time for a single addition operation is Ta time units.
[src:futhark-lang/data-parallelism] In the case of sequential execution, the time taken by the process will be *n*×Ta time units as it sums up all the elements of an array.
[src:futhark-lang/data-parallelism] On the other hand, if we execute this job as a data parallel job on 4 processors the time taken would reduce to (*n*/4)×Ta + merging overhead time units.
[src:futhark-lang/data-parallelism] Parallel execution results in a speedup of 4 over sequential execution.
[src:futhark-lang/data-parallelism] The locality of data references plays an important part in evaluating the performance of a data parallel programming model.
[src:futhark-lang/data-parallelism] Locality of data depends on the memory accesses performed by the program as well as the size of the cache.
[src:futhark-lang/data-parallelism] Exploitation of the concept of data parallelism started in 1960s with the development of the Solomon machine.
[src:futhark-lang/data-parallelism] The Solomon machine, also called a vector processor, was developed to expedite the performance of mathematical operations by working on a large data array (operating on multiple data in consecutive time steps).
[src:futhark-lang/data-parallelism] Concurrency of data operations was also exploited by operating on multiple data at the same time using a single instruction.
[src:futhark-lang/data-parallelism] These processors were called 'array processors'.
[src:futhark-lang/data-parallelism] In the 1980s, the term was introduced to describe this programming style, which was widely used to program Connection Machines in data parallel languages like C*.
[src:futhark-lang/data-parallelism] Today, data parallelism is best exemplified in graphics processing units (GPUs), which use both the techniques of operating on multiple data in space and time using a single instruction.
[src:futhark-lang/data-parallelism] Most data parallel hardware supports only a fixed number of parallel levels, often only one.
[src:futhark-lang/data-parallelism] This means that within a parallel operation it is not possible to launch more parallel operations recursively, and means that programmers cannot make use of nested hardware parallelism.
[src:futhark-lang/data-parallelism] The programming language NESL was an early effort at implementing a nested data-parallel programming model on flat parallel machines, and in particular introduced the flattening transformation that transforms nested data parallelism to flat data parallelism.
[src:futhark-lang/data-parallelism] This work was continued by other languages such as Data Parallel Haskell and Futhark, although arbitrary nested data parallelism is not widely available in current data-parallel programming languages.
[src:futhark-lang/data-parallelism] In a multiprocessor system executing a single set of instructions (SIMD), data parallelism is achieved when each processor performs the same task on different distributed data.
[src:futhark-lang/data-parallelism] In some situations, a single execution thread controls operations on all the data.
[src:futhark-lang/data-parallelism] In others, different threads control the operation, but they execute the same code.
[src:futhark-lang/data-parallelism] For instance, consider matrix multiplication and addition in a sequential manner as discussed in the example.
[src:futhark-lang/data-parallelism] Below is the sequential pseudo-code for multiplication and addition of two matrices where the result is stored in the matrix *C*.
[src:futhark-lang/data-parallelism] The pseudo-code for multiplication calculates the dot product of two matrices *A*, *B* and stores the result into the output matrix *C*.
[src:futhark-lang/data-parallelism] If the following programs were executed sequentially, the time taken to calculate the result would be of the $O(n^{3})$ (assuming row lengths and column lengths of both matrices are n) and $O(n)$ for multiplication and addition respectively.
[src:futhark-lang/data-parallelism] We can exploit data parallelism in the preceding code to execute it faster as the arithmetic is loop independent.
[src:futhark-lang/data-parallelism] Parallelization of the matrix multiplication code is achieved by using OpenMP.
[src:futhark-lang/data-parallelism] An OpenMP directive, "omp parallel for" instructs the compiler to execute the code in the for loop in parallel.
[src:futhark-lang/data-parallelism] For multiplication, we can divide matrix A and B into blocks along rows and columns respectively.
[src:futhark-lang/data-parallelism] This allows us to calculate every element in matrix C individually thereby making the task parallel.
[src:futhark-lang/data-parallelism] For example: *A[m x n] dot B [n x k]* can be finished in $O(n)$ instead of $O(m*n*k)$ when executed in parallel using *m*k* processors.
[src:futhark-lang/data-parallelism] It can be observed from the example that a lot of processors will be required as the matrix sizes keep on increasing.
[src:futhark-lang/data-parallelism] Keeping the execution time low is the priority but as the matrix size increases, we are faced with other constraints like complexity of such a system and its associated costs.
[src:futhark-lang/data-parallelism] Therefore, constraining the number of processors in the system, we can still apply the same principle and divide the data into bigger chunks to calculate the product of two matrices.
[src:futhark-lang/data-parallelism] For addition of arrays in a data parallel implementation, let's assume a more modest system with two central processing units (CPU) A and B, CPU A could add all elements from the top half of the arrays, while CPU B could add all elements from the bottom half of the arrays.
[src:futhark-lang/data-parallelism] Since the two processors work in parallel, the job of performing array addition would take one half the time of performing the same operation in serial using one CPU alone.
[src:futhark-lang/data-parallelism] In an SPMD system executed on 2 processor system, both CPUs will execute the code.
[src:futhark-lang/data-parallelism] Data parallelism emphasizes the distributed (parallel) nature of the data, as opposed to the processing (task parallelism).
[src:futhark-lang/data-parallelism] Most real programs fall somewhere on a continuum between task parallelism and data parallelism.
[src:futhark-lang/data-parallelism] The process of parallelizing a sequential program can be broken down into four discrete steps.
[src:futhark-lang/data-parallelism] Data and task parallelism, can be simultaneously implemented by combining them together for the same application.
[src:futhark-lang/data-parallelism] This is called Mixed data and task parallelism.
[src:futhark-lang/data-parallelism] Mixed parallelism requires sophisticated scheduling algorithms and software support.
[src:futhark-lang/data-parallelism] It is the best kind of parallelism when communication is slow and number of processors is large.
[src:futhark-lang/data-parallelism] Mixed data and task parallelism has many applications.
[src:futhark-lang/data-parallelism] The data is divided among different sub-circuits and parallelism is achieved with orchestration from the tasks.
[src:futhark-lang/data-parallelism] OpenMP: It's an Application Programming Interface (API) which supports shared memory programming models on multiple platforms of multiprocessor systems.
[src:futhark-lang/data-parallelism] Since version 4.5, OpenMP is also able to target devices other than typical CPUs.
[src:futhark-lang/data-parallelism] It can program FPGAs, DSPs, GPUs and more.
[src:futhark-lang/data-parallelism] It is not confined to GPUs like OpenACC.
[src:futhark-lang/data-parallelism] CUDA and OpenACC: CUDA and OpenACC (respectively) are parallel computing API platforms designed to allow a software engineer to utilize GPUs' computational units for general purpose processing.
[src:futhark-lang/data-parallelism] Threading Building Blocks and RaftLib: Both open source programming environments that enable mixed data/task parallelism in C/C++ environments across heterogeneous resources.
[src:futhark-lang/data-parallelism] Data parallelism finds its applications in a variety of fields ranging from physics, chemistry, biology, material sciences to signal processing.
[src:futhark-lang/data-parallelism] Sciences imply data parallelism for simulating models like molecular dynamics, sequence analysis of genome data and other physical phenomenon.
[src:futhark-lang/data-parallelism] Driving forces in signal processing for data parallelism are video encoding, image and graphics processing, wireless communications to name a few.
[src:futhark-lang/data-parallelism] Data-intensive computing is a class of parallel computing applications which use a data parallel approach to process large volumes of data typically terabytes or petabytes in size and typically referred to as big data.
[src:futhark-lang/data-parallelism] Computing applications that devote most of their execution time to computational requirements are deemed compute-intensive, whereas applications are deemed data-intensive if they require large volumes of data and devote most of their processing time to input/output and manipulation of data.
[src:futhark-lang/docs] The Futhark documentation is divided into several parts.
[src:futhark-lang/docs] The in-progress book Parallel Programming in Futhark can be read freely online, and is the starting point for learning Futhark.
[src:futhark-lang/docs] The Futhark User's Guide contains detailed instructions on how to use the compilers, as well as the language reference and instructions on how to install the Futhark compiler.
[src:futhark-lang/docs] There is also automatically generated documentation for the Futhark prelude.
[src:futhark-lang/docs] The prelude library is very small, so in most cases you will want to use external packages.
[src:futhark-lang/docs] If there is something you believe should be documented, but is not, you are very welcome to report the omission as a bug on our bug tracker.
[src:futhark-lang/docs] See the page Get Involved for more information.
[src:futhark-lang/docs] The Futhark compiler can generate C or Python code.
[src:futhark-lang/docs] A bridge allows programs written in other languages to conveniently call this code.
[src:futhark-lang/futhark-programming-language] Futhark is a language in the ML family, with an indentation-insensitive syntax derived from OCaml, Standard ML, and Haskell.
[src:futhark-lang/futhark-programming-language] The type system is based on a Hindley–Milner type system with a variety of extensions, such as uniqueness types and size-dependent types.
[src:futhark-lang/futhark-programming-language] Futhark is not intended as a general-purpose programming language for writing full applications, but is instead focused on writing *compute kernels* (not always the same as a *GPU kernel*) which are then invoked from applications written in conventional languages.
[src:futhark-lang/futhark-programming-language] Futhark is named after the first six letters of the Runic alphabet.
[src:futhark-lang/futhark-programming-language] The following program computes the dot product of two vectors containing double-precision numbers.
[src:futhark-lang/futhark-programming-language] It can also be equivalently written with explicit type annotations as follows.
[src:futhark-lang/futhark-programming-language] This makes the size-dependent types explicit: this function can only be invoked with two arrays of the same size, and the type checker will reject any program where this cannot be statically determined.
[src:futhark-lang/futhark-programming-language] The following program performs matrix multiplication, using the definition of dot product above.
[src:futhark-lang/futhark-programming-language] This shows how the types enforce that the function is only invoked with matrices of compatible size.
[src:futhark-lang/futhark-programming-language] Also, it is an example of nested data parallelism.
[src:futhark-lang/purely-functional-programming] In computer science, **purely functional programming** usually designates a programming paradigm—a style of building the structure and elements of computer programs—that treats all computation as the evaluation of mathematical functions.
[src:futhark-lang/purely-functional-programming] This style handles state changes without losing the referential transparency of the program expressions.
[src:futhark-lang/purely-functional-programming] Purely functional programming consists of ensuring that functions, inside the functional paradigm, will only depend on their arguments, regardless of any global or local state.
[src:futhark-lang/purely-functional-programming] A pure functional subroutine only has visibility of changes of state represented by state variables included in its scope.
[src:futhark-lang/purely-functional-programming] The exact difference between pure and impure functional programming is a matter of controversy.
[src:futhark-lang/purely-functional-programming] Sabry's proposed definition of purity is that all common evaluation strategies (call-by-name, call-by-value, and call-by-need) produce the same result, ignoring strategies that error or diverge.
[src:futhark-lang/purely-functional-programming] A program is usually said to be functional when it uses some concepts of functional programming, such as first-class functions and higher-order functions.
[src:futhark-lang/purely-functional-programming] However, a first-class function need not be purely functional, as it may use techniques from the imperative paradigm, such as arrays or input/output methods that use mutable cells, which update their state as side effects.
[src:futhark-lang/purely-functional-programming] In fact, the earliest programming languages cited as being functional, IPL and Lisp, are both "impure" functional languages by Sabry's definition.
[src:futhark-lang/purely-functional-programming] Each evaluation strategy which ends on a purely functional program returns the same result.
[src:futhark-lang/purely-functional-programming] In particular, it ensures that the programmer does not have to consider in which order programs are evaluated, since eager evaluation will return the same result as lazy evaluation.
[src:futhark-lang/purely-functional-programming] However, it is still possible that an eager evaluation may not terminate while the lazy evaluation of the same program halts.
[src:futhark-lang/purely-functional-programming] An advantage of this is that lazy evaluation can be implemented much more easily; as all expressions will return the same result at any moment (regardless of program state), their evaluation can be delayed as much as necessary.
[src:futhark-lang/purely-functional-programming] In a purely functional language, the only dependencies between computations are data dependencies, and computations are deterministic.
[src:futhark-lang/purely-functional-programming] Therefore, to program in parallel, the programmer need only specify the pieces that should be computed in parallel, and the runtime can handle all other details such as distributing tasks to processors, managing synchronization and communication, and collecting garbage in parallel.
[src:futhark-lang/purely-functional-programming] This style of programming avoids common issues such as race conditions and deadlocks, but has less control than an imperative language.
[src:futhark-lang/purely-functional-programming] To ensure a speedup, the granularity of tasks must be carefully chosen to be neither too big nor too small.
[src:futhark-lang/purely-functional-programming] In theory, it is possible to use runtime profiling and compile-time analysis to judge whether introducing parallelism will speed up the program, and thus automatically parallelize purely functional programs.
[src:futhark-lang/purely-functional-programming] In practice, this has not been terribly successful, and fully automatic parallelization is not practical.
[src:futhark-lang/purely-functional-programming] Purely functional data structures are persistent.
[src:futhark-lang/purely-functional-programming] Persistency is required for functional programming; without it, the same computation could return different results.
[src:futhark-lang/purely-functional-programming] Functional programming may use persistent non-purely functional data structures, while those data structures may not be used in purely functional programs.
[src:futhark-lang/purely-functional-programming] Purely functional data structures are often represented in a different way than their imperative counterparts.
[src:futhark-lang/purely-functional-programming] For example, array with constant-time access and update is a basic component of most imperative languages and many imperative data-structures, such as hash table and binary heap, are based on arrays.
[src:futhark-lang/purely-functional-programming] Arrays can be replaced by map or random access list, which admits purely functional implementation, but the access and update time is logarithmic.
[src:futhark-lang/purely-functional-programming] Therefore, purely functional data structures can be used in languages which are non-functional, but they may not be the most efficient tool available, especially if persistency is not required.
[src:futhark-lang/purely-functional-programming] In general, conversion of an imperative program to a purely functional one also requires ensuring that the formerly-mutable structures are now explicitly returned from functions that update them, a program structure called store-passing style.
[src:futhark-lang/purely-functional-programming] A purely functional language is a language which only admits purely functional programming.
[src:futhark-lang/purely-functional-programming] Purely functional programs can however be written in languages which are not purely functional.
